Who is LSP
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  LSP was initially designed at Microsoft to power their new text editor, VSCode
-->
LSP was initially designed at Microsoft to power their new text editor. You may
have heard of it... VSCode!
<!--end_slide-->
When is LSP
--

<!-- speaker_note: initial commit in 2015 and open sourced in 2016-->
The initial commit for LSP was in 2015 when Microsoft started work on VSCode
with it being open sourced in 2016.

<!-- speaker_note: silently, or not so silently, powering editor tooling ever since!-->
Powering tooling in editors such as VSCode, Neovim, Zed and more for years!
<!--end_slide-->
What is LSP
--

<!-- 
  speaker_note: |
  LSP the specification that Language Servers use to talk to Clents (Generally 
  text editors). More on that later
-->

Language Server Protocol, or `LSP`, is a specification that aims to
standardize communication between `Language Servers` and `Clients.` More on
those later

<!--end_slide-->
Where is LSP
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  The spec is open source and is likely currently running inside your editor
  Some other places you might see it are browser editors, AI agents, and the 
  Symbols tab in GitHub (Technically not LSP, but LSIF)
-->

The specification is [Open Source](https://microsoft.github.io/language-server-protocol/).

It likely powers the editor you use everyday, as well as other tools like:

- In browser editors like Monaco and CodeMirror
- Inside AI Agents like OpenCode and Goose
- The Symbols tab on GitHub (That's technically `LSIF`, the sister to `LSP`)

<!--end_slide-->
Why is LSP
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  Each tool needs custom code to handle each language for autocomplete, symbols,
  refactors, etc.

  each tool has one LSP client (Generally) and each language has one
  Language Server (Hopefully).
-->

Each tool needs custom code to handle each language for autocomplete, symbols,
refactors, etc.

With LSP each tool has `one` LSP client (Generally) and each language has `one`
Language Server (Hopefully).

<!--end_slide-->
Why is LSP: Table
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  LSP takes us from `x*y` to `x+y` in terms of the number of 
  implementations that need to maintained
 -->

