Basics of IPC
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  IPC, or Inter-process Communication is how one piece of software talks to another. 

  This is generally on the same machine, but network requests utilizing sockets 
  are another method of IPC.

  - Small aside about how presenterm uses IPC to communicate between publisher 
  and listener for speaker notes

  LSP utilizes STDIO for communication. It is a direct link from a parent process
  to a child process. This is the stuff you see and interact with when running 
  commands in a shell.
  
  STDIO is comprised of:

  - stdin
    - standard input
    - how the parent process gets information into the child process
    - How LSP clients send messages to language servers
  - stdout
    - standard output
    - one of the ways the child process gets data back to the parent process
    - this is the primary avenue for language servers to respond to requests
    and send notifications
  - stderr
    - standard error
    - the other way the child process gets data back to the parent process
    - language servers usually use stderr for logging as not to pollute stdout
    and break the JSON RPC

 -->

`IPC` is how one piece of software talks to another, usually on the same machine.

`LSP` generally uses `STDIO` for communication. It is comprised of:

- `stdin`
- `stdout`
- `stderr`

<!--end_slide-->
Defining JSON RPC
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  JSON RPC is a simple protocol for using JSON messages to handle remote 
  procedure calls. It is transport agnostic, so you can have JSON RPC API's 
  over HTTP as well as something like STDIO.

  Quick disclaimer, when I say "structured data", I am talking about either 
  positional args via arrays, or key value pairs via objects

  There are 4 main object types:
  - Requests
    - Used to call remote procedures on a server. Sometimes expecting a response 
    in return
    - An example would be requesting hover definition
  - Responses
    - Used to get data from the server back to the client, generally in response
    to a request
    - Can be either a be a success or error
    - An example would be the result of that hover definition
  - Client Notifications
    - Sent by clients when they want to call a procedure but do not expect a response
    - An example would be the client telling the server when a new file has been 
    opened
  - Server Notifications
    - Sent by servers to notify clients of changes without the client needing to 
    send a request prior
    - An example might be a server sending diagnostic informtion to a client after 
    running validation

-->

`JSON RPC` is a simple protocol for using `JSON` messages to handle remote
procedure calls. It is transport agnostic, so you can have `JSON RPC` API's
over `HTTP` as well as something like `STDIO`.

There are 4 main object types:

- Requests
- Responses
- Client Notifications
- Server Notifications
<!--end_slide-->
LSP Components
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  lSP uses two distinct components:
  - Language Servers
    - How you interact with a `Language Server`. Takes LSP responses/notifications
    and can perform actions on them.
    - The brains of the operation where all the language specific code lives
  - Clients
    - Handles language specific details. Computes diagnostics, keeps track of symbols,
    and can offer refactors (sometimes called `Code Actions`)
    - Sort of like the senses for the brain, taking in information and responding 
    to notifications
 -->

The `LSP` spec defines 2 distinct components:

- `Clients`
  - How you interact with a `Language Server`. Takes LSP responses/notifications
  and can perform actions on them.
- `Language Servers`
  - Handles language specific details. Computes diagnostics, keeps track of symbols,
  and can offer refactors (sometimes called `Code Actions`)
<!--end_slide-->
Language Servers
--
<!--
    speaker_note: |
    - A process that gets started and owned by the Client to handle requests and
    emit notifications
    - Where all the language specific code lives
    - Fully decoupled from the details of the client
    - Likely a standalone executable like rust-analyzer or gopls, or might be 
    part of an existing toolchain like the Gleam language server. It could also
    be a library that needs to use another runtime like the Typescript language 
    server
-->
A process that gets started and owned by the `Client` to handle requests and
emit notifications

Where all the language specific code lives

Decoupled from the details of the `Client`

<!--end_slide-->
LSP Clients
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  - Spawns the a Language Server process for each filetype opened and owns them
  for the life of editing session
  - How you communicate with the Language Server
  - Generic for all Language Servers (Usually)
  - Usually a text editor, but might be an AI agent or some other process that
  needs to inspect code
-->

Spawns and manages `Language Server` processes and communication with them using
`IPC` (Coming up next)

Takes actions inside of the source software based on responses and notifications.

Generic for all `Language Servers` (_hopefully_)

<!--end_slide-->
Protocol Message Structure
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  A spec compliant message is comprised of two separate sections separated by a 
  carriage return and newline, very similar to HTTP:
  1. Header part
    - Metadata about the message
  2. Content part
    - The actual JSON data of the message

-->

The spec divides messages into two parts separated by `\r\n`:

- Header part
  - Metadata about the message
- Content part
  - The actual data of the message in `JSON` form.

<!--end_slide-->
Message Headers
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  The Header part is a set of "headers" the describe the message being sent. 
  These are newline delimited, colon separated key/value pairs. There are only 
  two spec compliant headers:
  - Content-Length
    - Required
    - The length of the content part in bytes
    - example: The content part of the message is 16 bytes long
  - Content-Type
    - Optional
    - The mime type of the `content part`
    - example: The content type of the message is standard JSON

  I am not very familiar with the `application/vscode-jsonrpc` mime type, but
  I would assume is effectively just JSON.
-->

Two spec compliant headers:

- Content-Length
  - Required
  - The length of the `content part` in bytes
  - example: `Content-Length: 16\r\n`
- Content-Type
  - Optional
  - The mime type of the `content part`
  - defaults to `application/vscode-jsonrpc;charset=utf-8`
  - example: `Content-Type: application/json\r\n`

<!--end_slide-->
Message Content
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  The content part is a JSON encoded message that follows the JSON RPC spec. That 
  is the JSON data should conform to one of the 4 message types described earlier. 

-->

Example JSON RPC Message:

```json
Content-Length: 118\r\n
\r\n
{
  "jsonrpc": "2.0",
  "id": "1",
  "method": "namespace/methodName",
  "params": {
    "someParam": "PhillyJS"
  }
}
```

<!--end_slide-->
Common Messages
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  The LSP spec is pretty in depth, so I couldn't possibly cover it in this short 
  talk. I will however cover a couple of the most common message types that are 
  used, at least in my own editing and workflows

  Autocomplete:

  Completions are probably the quintessential feature of LSP. Getting suggestions
  while you are typing is so helpful, especially for someone like me who is absolutely
  not a good typist.

  Go to definition/declaration/definition/implementation and Find References:

  This feature is so useful for navigating large codebases. Not needing to know
  where every thing is defined all the time is very helpful. This makes it a breeze 
  to find what you're looking for without having to resort to grep 
  (Not that I don't love grep)

  Code Lenses/Code Actions:

  Along the same lines as autocomplete, I love when I can automate tidium with 
  minimal cost. One of my favorite language servers is the one for Gleam. They provide
  SO MANY great code actions.

  Diagnostics:

  I mean who doesn't love thier editor yelling at them before they've finished 
  typing. In reality getting feedback about possible issues in my project without 
  having to leave my text buffer streamlines my process so much

-->

Some common features that you might not know are powered by LSP.

- Autocomplete
- Go to definition/declaration/definition/implementation
- Find References
- Code Lenses/Code Actions
- Diagnostics

<!--end_slide-->
Negotiating Capabilities
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  Language servers and LSP clients don't need to support every feature of the spec. 
  During initialization, the Client and Server exchange what capabilities
  they support. A capability is just a particular feature or action that is
  part of the spec.

  The client uses the capabilities field on the InitialzeParams type when
  calling the initialize method. The server then responds with an InitializeResult
  that includes a similar capabilities field that describes the server capabilities

  Finally the client sends back a notification with the "initialized" method to 
  finalize the process and start sharing document data.
-->

```mermaid +render
sequenceDiagram
  participant c as Client
  participant s as Server
  c->>s: Send an initialize request with the<br/>capabilities the client supports
  s->>c: Send an initialize response with the<br/>capabilities the server supports
  c-)s: Send an initialized notification to ack <br/> the initialize response
```

<!--end_slide-->
Document Synchronization
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  Language Servers need to know about the documents we are editing to do anything 
  useful with said documents. We manage this state using a handful of 
  "document synchronization" methods. These include:
  
  - `textDocument/didOpen`
    - Sent when you first open a document to notify the language server so
    it can do things like compute diagnostics
  - `textDocument/didChange`
    - Sent when you you make an edit to an existing document so the language server
    can _recompute_ things like diagnostics
  - `textDocument/didClose`
    - Sent when you close a document so the language server can cleanup any resources
    tied to that document

-->

- `textDocument/didOpen`
  - Sent when you first open a document to notify the language server so
    it can do things like compute diagnostics
- `textDocument/didChange`
  - Sent when you you make an edit to an existing document so the language server
    can _recompute_ things like diagnostics
- `textDocument/didClose`
  - Sent when you close a document so the language server can cleanup any resources
    tied to that document
<!--end_slide-->
Document Synchronization Example
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |
  Here is an example of what document synchronization might look like. We start 
  with the client notifying the server that it has opened a new document. The
  server then computes diagnostics for that document, in this case there are none
  as the file is in a good state.
  
  Next we make a broken change to that file and notify the server of our changes.
  The server recomputes the diagnostics and sends back another notification, this
  time with information about where our code is broken.

  Note that these are all notifications, so this is entirely asynchronous. These
  steps are not dependent on one another (Except the didOpen and didChange) notifications
  from the client.
-->
```mermaid +render
sequenceDiagram
  participant c as Client
  participant s as Server
  c--)s: Send a `textDocument/didOpen`<br/>notification with file with now issues
  s--)c: Send a `textDocument/publishDiagnostics`<br/>with no diagnostics
  c--)s: Send a `textDocument/didChange`<br/>notification with a file with issues
  s--)c: Send a `textDocument/publishDiagnostics`<br/>with diagnostics for those issues
```
<!--end_slide-->
Sample Message: Diagnostics
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  This is a notification the server sends to the client whenever it recomputes 
  diagnostic information for a particular document. The document's URI is given
  on line 4, with the diagnostics being an array of objects that include 
  information such as:
  - The text range of the diagnostic
    - Line 7
    - This is an object that tells the client _where_ this diagnostics needs to 
    be represented in the document. It includes the start and end positions. 
    I just ran out of space here
  - The severity of the diagnostic
    - Line 8
    - This tells the client the "severity level" of the diagnostic. It is an 
    enum that represents values such as:
      - Error
      - Warning
      - Hint
  - The diagnostic message:
    - Line 9
    - This is a required field that tells the client what the actual diagnostic 
    _means_. You have this field to thank for those ungodly monstrosities they 
    call "Typescript Errors"
-->

```json +line_numbers
{
    "method": "textDocument/publishDiagnostics",
    "params": {
      "uri": "file:///path/to/file.ts",
      "diagnostics": [
        {
          "range": {...},
          "severity": 1,
          "message": "BROKEN :("
        }
      ]
    }
}
```

<!--end_slide-->
Sample Flow: Autocomplete - Diagram
--

```mermaid +render
sequenceDiagram
  participant c as Client
  participant s as Server
  c->>+s: Send a `textDocument/completion`<br/>request with the document uri and position
  s->>-c: Send a `textDocument/completion`<br/>response a list of completions
  c->>c: The selected completion is applied
  Note over c: The inserted text can from one<br/> of three fields on the completion:<br/>1.textEdit<br/>2.insertText<br/>3.label
```
<!--end_slide-->
Sample Flow: Autocomplete - Request
--
<!--
  speaker_note: |

  An example of a request for completions. This message includes the text 
  document and position said text document that the server needs to look at to 
  compute a completion list.

  In this case we are looking at line 19 character 93 inside of file.ts
-->

```json +line_numbers
{
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 42,
    "method": "textDocument/completion",
    "params": {
      "textDocument": {
        "uri": "file:///path/to/file.ts"
      },
      "position": {
          "line": 19,
          "character": 93
      }
    }
}
```

<!--end_slide-->
Sample Flow: Autocomplete - Response
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |

  This is what a response from the server might look like. The ID matches our 
  request ID, and the result field is an array of completion objects. This example 
  only shows one very simplistic completion because I ran out of room.

  The suggestion we have has a label of "Text Suggestion" and a kind of 1. Kind 
  is an enum that maps to various kinds of completions. In this case it is 
  consdered a "Text" completion.

  This list likely has many other suggestions, and they can include other fields 
  that tell the client what to do if that completion is selected or additional 
  details about the completion.

  If only the "label" is supplied, the client will just insert the label text 
  upon selecting that completion.
-->

```json
{
    "jsonrpc": "2.0",
    "id": 42,
    "result": [
      {
        "label": "Text Suggestion", 
        "kind": 1,
      },
      // ...other items
    ]
}
```

<!--end_slide-->
Basic LSP Client
--

<!--
  speaker_note: |
  I had initially planned on digging into the TypeScript language server
  code, but that stuff is **dense**. So instead I put together a little example
  of a client that we can use to interact with a language server and see what the
  communication looks like!

  With Microsoft again putting a wrench in my plan, the Typescript LSP is... _weird_. So
  we will be looking at the Go language server: `gopls`!
-->

I had initially planned on digging into the TypeScript language server
code, but that stuff is **dense**. So instead I put together a little example
of a client that we can use to interact with a language server and see what the
communication looks like!

With Microsoft again putting a wrench in my plan, the Typescript LSP is... _weird_. So
we will be looking at the Go language server: `gopls`!
